+    \subsection{Hyperbolic Parameterization of Bounded Tangential Swirl Fractions}
+    \label{app:golden_hyperbolic_parameterization}
+
+    \statusCanonical\ This subsection records a canon-permitted \emph{kinematic}
+    parameterization for bounded tangential swirl fractions and an optional
+    golden-marker coordinate choice. It is a notation/normalization aid and
+    does not by itself constitute a dynamical law, stability criterion, or
+    spectral prediction.
+
+    \paragraph{Bounded tangential fraction.}
+    Define the dimensionless tangential fraction
+    \begin{equation}
+        \beta \;\equiv\; \frac{\lVert \mathbf{v} \rVert}{\lVert \mathbf{v}_{\!\boldsymbol{\circlearrowleft}} \rVert},
+        \qquad 0 \le \beta < 1,
+    \end{equation}
+    where $\lVert \mathbf{v}_{\!\boldsymbol{\circlearrowleft}} \rVert$ is the canonical
+    characteristic swirl speed and $\lVert \mathbf{v} \rVert$ is the local/sector speed
+    being expressed as a bounded fraction.
+
+    \paragraph{Hyperbolic coordinate map.}
+    A bijective bounded-coordinate parameterization is
+    \begin{equation}
+        \beta \;=\; \tanh \xi,
+        \qquad
+        \xi \;=\; \operatorname{artanh}(\beta),
+        \label{eq:beta_tanh_xi_appendix}
+    \end{equation}
+    with the correct limits $\xi\to 0 \Rightarrow \beta\to 0$ and
+    $\xi\to \infty \Rightarrow \beta\to 1^{-}$.
+
+    \paragraph{Optional golden-marker coordinate.}
+    Let $\phi=(1+\sqrt{5})/2$ denote the golden ratio. Define
+    \begin{equation}
+        \xi_g \;\equiv\; \frac{3}{2}\,\operatorname{asinh}\!\left(\frac{1}{2}\right).
+        \label{eq:xi_g_def_appendix}
+    \end{equation}
+    Then one has the identity
+    \begin{equation}
+        \tanh(\xi_g) \;=\; \phi^{-1}.
+        \label{eq:tanh_xig_phi_appendix}
+    \end{equation}
+    This permits the optional shorthand
+    \begin{equation}
+        \beta_g \;\equiv\; \phi^{-1}
+        \qquad\Longleftrightarrow\qquad
+        \xi=\xi_g
+    \end{equation}
+    as a distinguished \emph{kinematic marker} in the hyperbolic coordinate.
+
+    \paragraph{Derived kinematic scales (normalization only).}
+    If one chooses to evaluate the marker against the canonical constants
+    $\lVert \mathbf{v}_{\!\boldsymbol{\circlearrowleft}} \rVert$ and $r_c$, the associated
+    speed and angular-frequency scales are
+    \begin{equation}
+        \lVert \mathbf{v} \rVert_g \;=\; \frac{\lVert \mathbf{v}_{\!\boldsymbol{\circlearrowleft}} \rVert}{\phi},
+        \qquad
+        \Omega_g \;=\; \frac{\lVert \mathbf{v}_{\!\boldsymbol{\circlearrowleft}} \rVert}{\phi\,r_c}.
+        \label{eq:golden_marker_scales_appendix}
+    \end{equation}
+    These are \emph{dimensional/kinematic} normalization scales only. They are not,
+    by themselves, a prediction of resonant frequencies, layer occupation, or
+    dynamical selection without a sector-specific SST model.
+
+    \paragraph{Canonical usage note.}
+    \statusResearch\ The golden-marker parameterization may be used in DSI/golden-layer
+    discussions as a bounded-coordinate convenience. Any claim that it determines
+    a universal exponent, a preferred dynamical layer, or a measurable resonance
+    requires separate derivation and quantitative falsifiers.
 
     \subsection{Physical Analogy}
         Consider Conway notation as the structural chemical formula for a molecule, where ``tangles'' are functional groups snapping together. Alexander-Briggs is merely the common name (like ``water''), and Dowker-Thistlethwaite is a database registry number. Reidemeister moves represent bending or twisting the molecule without breaking any chemical bonds.
